# SOAP Handler ‚Äì SOAP to REST Converter

The **SOAP Handler** in OpenFusionAPI enables transforming SOAP web services into REST endpoints, allowing modern applications to consume legacy SOAP services easily.  
Internally, it uses the official `soap` Node.js library for communication and structure handling.

---

<details>
<summary>üß† How It Works</summary>

1. The user sends a REST request to an endpoint configured with the SOAP handler.  
2. OpenFusionAPI creates a SOAP client using the provided **WSDL** and **endpoint** configuration.  
3. The requested SOAP function is executed with the parameters defined in the request.  
4. The SOAP response is automatically converted into **JSON** and returned to the REST client.  
5. Any errors returned by the SOAP service or connection are handled and sent back as HTTP 500 responses.

</details>

<details>
<summary>üìÑ SOAP Service Configuration</summary>

The SOAP handler requires the following JSON structure to be set in the configuration or as an Application Variable:

```json
{
  "wsdl": "https://www.dataaccess.com/webservicesserver/numberconversion.wso?WSDL",
  "endpoint": "https://www.dataaccess.com/webservicesserver/numberconversion.wso",
  "functionName": "NumberToDollars",
  "BasicAuthSecurity": {
    "User": "any",
    "Password": "any"
  },
  "RequestArgs": {
    "dNum": 236.08
  }
}
```

![SOAP Configuration](data:image/png;base64,)

**Parameter Details:**

| Parameter | Description | Required |
|------------|-------------|-----------|
| **wsdl** | URL of the SOAP service WSDL. | ‚úÖ |
| **endpoint** | Optional SOAP endpoint URL. | ‚ùå |
| **functionName** | SOAP method to invoke. | ‚úÖ |
| **BasicAuthSecurity** | Authentication for SOAP call (optional). | ‚ùå |
| **RequestArgs** | Method arguments. | ‚úÖ |
| **options** | Additional SOAP client options. | ‚ùå |

> ‚ö†Ô∏è Parameters configured here will override any parameters sent in the HTTP request.

</details>

---

<details>
<summary>üì§ Example Request and Response</summary>

**Endpoint:** `/api/demo/soap/numbertodollars`

### Example Request (POST)

```bash
curl -X POST https://yourserver.com/api/demo/soap/numbertodollars \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "wsdl": "https://www.dataaccess.com/webservicesserver/numberconversion.wso?WSDL",
    "endpoint": "https://www.dataaccess.com/webservicesserver/numberconversion.wso",
    "functionName": "NumberToDollars",
    "RequestArgs": {
      "dNum": 3.65
    }
  }'
```

### Example Response (200 OK)
```json
{
  "NumberToDollarsResult": "three dollars and sixty five cents"
}
```

</details>

---

<details>
<summary>üß† Advanced Usage</summary>

To dynamically obtain the structure of a SOAP service, you can send the following request body:

```json
{ "describe()": true }
```

The result will include available operations, data types, and namespaces ‚Äî equivalent to using `client.describe()` in the Node.js `soap` library.

</details>

---

<details>
<summary>üîê Authentication & Security</summary>

The SOAP handler supports:

- **Public** endpoints  
- **Basic Authentication**  
- **Token-based Authentication (JWT)**

Additionally, SOAP-level authentication may be configured using the fields `BasicAuthSecurity` or `BearerSecurity` inside the handler configuration.

Custom SOAP headers and WS-Security tokens can also be defined using the **options** field.

</details>

---

<details>
<summary>ü™µ Logging & Error Handling</summary>

All requests made through the SOAP handler are logged in the OpenFusionAPI global logging system, including:

- Timestamp  
- SOAP method executed  
- Execution time (ms)  
- HTTP status  
- Error messages (if any)

Errors return HTTP `500` and are formatted in JSON. The error message may include information from the SOAP response if available.

</details>

---

<details>
<summary>üíæ Caching</summary>

Caching behavior is identical to other handlers:  
- Set the cache time in seconds.  
- A value of **0** disables caching.  

</details>
